        "content": "<p>I'm looking to define the type of continuous maps vanishing at infinity. Does this seem like a reasonable start? I don't want to get too deep if I'm heading in the wrong direction somehow.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">topology.continuous_function.bounded</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\">/-</span><span class=\"cm\">!</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"># Continuous functions vanishing at infinity</span>\n\n<span class=\"cm\">The type of continuous functions vanishing at infinity. When the domain is a locally compact space,</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">this type has nice properties. When the domain is compact `C‚ÇÄ(Œ±, Œ≤) ‚âÉ C(Œ±, Œ≤)` via the identity map.</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">-/</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">universes</span> <span class=\"n\">u</span> <span class=\"n\">v</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">F</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">Œ±</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">Œ≤</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"o\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"n\">open_locale</span> <span class=\"n\">bounded_continuous_function</span>\n\n<span class=\"sd\">/-- `C‚ÇÄ(Œ±, Œ≤)` is the type of continuous functions `Œ± ‚Üí Œ≤` which vanish at infinity from a</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">topological space to a metric space with a zero element. -/</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">structure</span> <span class=\"n\">zero_at_infty_continuous_map</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Œ±</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">)</spa